Copyright.RotationInfo: All except SNO: collected in geomagnetic. Most sites recorded in geomagnetic. Some sites, e.g., 241a.edi, 270a.edi, etc, have variable ZROT, and we are inferring that principal axis rotation was applied to these, which needs to be undone. Tipper in geographic throughout. For archiving, we are rotating everything to geographic, even though this messes up the error bars. SNO: collected in geomagnetic, already rotated to geographic. No further rotation required.
Copyright.AdditionalInfo: Lithoprobe SNORCLE Transect MT; 146 sites from SNORCLE; magnetotelluric Broad band magnetotelluric data collected during Lithoprobe project. Slave-Northern Cordillera Lithospheric Evolution (SNORCLE) transect is aimed at unraveling the complex interrelationships between the terranes, and determining the subsurface nature of the terrane boundaries and their physical states. To address these themes, a magnetotelluric (MT) experiment was conducted in the northern cordillera during the summer and fall of 1999, and included three regional-scale profiles, which crossed the main geological structures, and a high-resolution profile crossing the Tintina Fault.
